as the library, so I'm considering defining a helper class instead, which aligns with the rule that tests should remain outside library packages.\\n\\nThere’s also the idea that if a public API triggers a certain class reference, it might create complications, like using MethodHandles that might not be covered due to the agent configuration. The method name \\\"class$\\\" feels odd too.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating method coverage concerns**\\n\\nI’m wondering if external workflows count only when methods are reached through public library behavior. But the coverage call site still exists. I think MethodHandle methods include the target frame in the stack, and it seems the instrumentation focuses on bytecode, not the stack.\\n\\nI'll consider that dynamic-access coverage might even use JaCoCo probes. Also, invoking package-private methods without line info might not be recorded. I’m unsure about using ByteBuddy for invocation. Perhaps I could access via Groovy's metaClass, but that feels risky. Direct reflection is discouraged unless absolutely necessary.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring access methods in Java**\\n\\nI’m considering that MethodHandles can quasi-reflect, but they’re already in use. I might add a custom test helper in a Java package outside, but calling a method would be tricky since access is prohibited due to package-private restrictions. I wonder about using `--patch-module` or `sun.misc.Unsafe`, but both options seem like no-goes. I think about GroovyShell too, but dynamic class loading isn’t supported in Native Image, which complicates things further.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating method invocation**\\n\\nI'm thinking it could fail before the call actually happens. If the invocation attempts to target before it returns, using the wrong method type might throw an error without calling the target. The expected return type seems to be a Class, but I wonder if I should use `(Clas